The `lock` statement in C# is used to ensure that a block of code runs by only one thread at a time, providing thread safety when accessing shared resources. It works by acquiring an exclusive lock on a specified object reference for the duration of the code block.

**Syntax:**
```csharp
lock (lockObject)
{
    // Critical section: code that accesses shared resources
}
```

**Example:**
```csharp
private readonly object _lock = new object();
private int _counter = 0;

public void IncrementCounter()
{
    lock (_lock)
    {
        _counter++;
        // Only one thread can execute this block at a time
